Pastry is not my forte, so I used puff pastry as the base and went from there. Liked the addition of thyme to the syrup. Very rustic looking, but made too much juice, which ran out and burned.

Rating: 3
A good recipe. It's basically like an apple pie without the top. The crust is flakey and buttery (very easily broken though). The thyme is also a very nice addition to the apples. Since they didn't have apple jelly in the store, I used 1/4 cup of blueberry and 1/4 cup of raspberry preserves. I suspect that you can substitute most jellies or jams into the recipe. Some tips: 1. Try to reduce the time to about 35 minutes (mine burnt a bit). 2. Be careful not to put too much wine on the apples (there was some spillage). 3. If you can, bake on parchment paper for easy cleanup. 4. If I were to make it again, I would divide the dough into eighths to create individual gallettes.

Rating: 4
My guests have always loved this, and so have I.

Rating: 4
I've been making this since it first appeared in Gourmet, and each time I make it, it's a great hit. Don't be afraid of the thyme. Its subtle flavors add to the galette's simplicity. Try it -- YOU WILL LOVE IT!

Rating: 0
I haven't made this particular recipe, but do plan to for Thanksgiving dinner this year. I wanted to add a suggestion re. filling the galette. The galette recipes I am familiar with (I often make one with a tomato/cheese filling as an appetizer) state that when the filling is spread over the crust, leave an uncovered, 2" border all the way around. Then when the filling is in place, fold the uncovered edge over the filling, pleating it as you go. Just a suggestion...but it does look lovely and rustic that way.

